data.content:
Yes! For simple inline cases, use `[DataRow]` — it's cleaner and type-safe:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need **computed/complex data** (where `DataRow` won't work since it requires compile-time constants), you can still use `DynamicData` but with tuples for type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData), DynamicDataDisplayName = nameof(GetDisplayName))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData =>
[
    [DateTime.Now.ToString(), true],  // computed — can't use DataRow
    ["invalid", false],
];

public static string GetDisplayName(MethodInfo _, object[] data)
    => $"Input: \"{data[0]}\" → {data[1]}";
```

**TL;DR:** Prefer `[DataRow]` for constant values. Reserve `DynamicData` for when you need runtime-generated test cases, and add a `DisplayName` method so test output stays readable.
